            {
                "@type": "Question",
                "name": "Does GST need to be re-registered when proprietorship converts to LLP?",
                "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes. The LLP is a new legal entity and obtains a fresh GSTIN through Form GST REG-01. The proprietorship GSTIN is cancelled via Form GST REG-16. Unutilised Input Tax Credit transfers via Form GST ITC-02 under Rule 41 of the CGST Rules 2017. The transfer of business as a going concern attracts nil GST under Notification 12/2017-Central Tax (Rate). Patron sequences both filings tightly to avoid double-GST exposure during the bridge period." }
            },
            {
                "@type": "Question",
                "name": "Why is there no Section 47(xiv) equivalent for LLP?",
                "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Section 47(xiv) of the Income Tax Act 1961 was drafted specifically for proprietorship-to-COMPANY conversion (with the 50% voting power 5-year lock-in being viable only in share-based structures). LLPs use capital contribution not equity shares, so the structural fit does not apply. Section 47(xiiib) exists for company-to-LLP conversion but again does not cover proprietorship-to-LLP. The slump sale route under Section 50B is the closest available tax treatment." }
            },
            {
                "@type": "Question",
                "name": "What if I want to upgrade further from LLP to Private Limited later?",
                "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Section 56 of the LLP Act 2008 allows conversion from LLP to private company through a specific procedure (CA-certified compliance with Section 56 + Third Schedule). This is a separate engagement; the original Section 50B slump sale tax position from the proprietorship-to-LLP move continues to apply to the LLP entity. Founders planning institutional fundraising within 18 months should consider the direct proprietorship-to-Pvt-Ltd route under Section 47(xiv) instead - that route is tax-neutral but heavier on compliance." }
