<!-- SECTION 2: OVERVIEW / INTRO + TL;DR -->
<section class="content-section" id="overview-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Proprietorship to LLP Conversion in Delhi - Overview</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-bottom:20px;">
                    <p><strong>&#128204; TL;DR - Proprietorship to LLP Conversion Services at a Glance</strong></p>
                    <p>There is no direct statutory conversion from sole proprietorship to LLP under Indian law. The mechanism is - incorporate a fresh LLP under the LLP Act 2008 via FiLLiP on MCA21 v3 (minimum 2 partners; no minimum capital), then transfer the proprietorship business to the LLP via a Business Transfer Agreement, typically structured as a slump sale under Section 50B of the Income Tax Act 1961. Patron INR 14,999 fixed.</p>
                </div>
                <p><div class='table-responsive-wrapper'>
                <table>
                    <thead><tr><th>Quick Reference</th><th>Details</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td>Governing Laws</td><td>LLP - Limited Liability Partnership Act 2008 + LLP Rules 2009. Business Transfer - Income Tax Act 1961 Section 50B (slump sale) read with Rule 11UAE; Indian Stamp Act 1899 (BTA stamp duty); CGST Act 2017 Notification 12/2017-CT(R) (going concern nil rate) read with Rule 41 CGST Rules 2017 (Form GST ITC-02)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Applicable To</td><td>Any sole proprietor in Delhi who can introduce at least one additional partner; LLP has no minimum capital requirement and no minimum turnover floor</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Timeline</td><td>End-to-end 15 to 30 days. DSC and DPIN 3-5 days; FiLLiP name reservation 3-5 days; Form 3 LLP Agreement within 30 days of incorporation; BTA + GST migration 7-10 days</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Cost (Patron)</td><td>INR 14,999 FIXED (Exl GST and Govt. Charges) - end-to-end including DSC, DPIN, FiLLiP, LLP Agreement, Form 3, BTA, GST migration, compliance kit</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Tax Position</td><td>Slump sale under Section 50B (capital gains at undertaking level - sale consideration minus net worth); Form 3CEA CA-certified. NO Section 47(xiv) tax neutrality (applies to company only).</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>LLP Minimums</td><td>2 designated partners (1 Indian resident under Section 7); no minimum capital; Form 3 within 30 days</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Authority</td><td>ROC NCT of Delhi and Haryana, CGO Complex; Central Registration Centre (CRC) for FiLLiP initial scrutiny</td></tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
                </div></p>
                <p>A sole proprietorship is the simplest Indian business form - one owner, no separate legal existence, unlimited personal liability, taxed at slab rates with the marginal rate climbing to 30% plus surcharge and cess as turnover grows. Most Delhi proprietors hit a wall around INR 1 to 5 crore turnover - banks need collateral that no longer covers personal exposure, B2B buyers prefer dealing with limited-liability entities, partners cannot be onboarded and income tax exposure crosses thresholds where corporate structures become economically rational. A Limited Liability Partnership (LLP) under the LLP Act 2008 fixes most of these problems - separate legal personality, limited partner liability, audit exemption below INR 40 lakh turnover and INR 25 lakh contribution, perpetual succession and partners on a structured agreement. Unlike the LLP Act's explicit conversion routes for partnership firms (Section 55), private companies (Section 56) and unlisted public companies (Section 57), there is no statutory provision to 'convert' a sole proprietorship to LLP - the practical mechanism is to incorporate a fresh LLP and transfer the proprietorship business via a Business Transfer Agreement, ideally structured as a slump sale under Section 50B of the Income Tax Act 1961.</p>
                <p>Content is reviewed quarterly for accuracy.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- SECTION 3: WHAT IS GSTAT APPEAL FILING -->
<section class="content-section" id="what-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="two-column">
            <div class="column-content">
                <h2 class="section-title">How Proprietorship Actually Becomes an LLP</h2>
                <div class="content-text what-is-definition">
                    
                    <p>The first thing to clarify - under Indian law, <strong>there is NO direct statutory route to "convert" a sole proprietorship into a Limited Liability Partnership.</strong> The Limited Liability Partnership Act 2008 explicitly provides conversion procedures for:</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Partnership firms</strong> - Section 55 read with the Second Schedule</li>
    <li><strong>Private companies</strong> - Section 56 read with the Third Schedule</li>
    <li><strong>Unlisted public companies</strong> - Section 57 read with the Fourth Schedule</li>
</ul>
<p>But the LLP Act is silent on sole proprietorships. This is because a sole proprietorship is not a separate legal entity in Indian law - it is the proprietor in personam, conducting business under a trade name. There is no separate juristic person to "convert".</p>

<p>The practical workflow is a two-step process. <strong>Step One</strong> - incorporate a fresh LLP under the LLP Act 2008 by filing the FiLLiP form on MCA21 v3 (this requires at least two designated partners, with at least one being an Indian resident under Section 7; no minimum capital). <strong>Step Two</strong> - transfer the business of the sole proprietorship to the newly incorporated LLP through a Business Transfer Agreement, typically structured as a slump sale under Section 50B of the Income Tax Act 1961 (the entire business is transferred as a going concern for a lump-sum consideration).</p>

<p>The proprietorship's GST registration is cancelled (Form GST REG-16), the LLP obtains its own GSTIN and the unutilised Input Tax Credit transfers via Form GST ITC-02 under Rule 41 of the CGST Rules 2017. Other licences and registrations (Udyam / MSME, Shop and Establishment, FSSAI, IEC, Profession Tax) are obtained afresh in the LLP's name. This is precisely what corporate service providers commonly call "proprietorship-to-LLP conversion" - the colloquial usage is universal even if the legal mechanism is not technically a conversion.</p>

<p>Delhi anchors this engagement because ROC NCT of Delhi and Haryana at CGO Complex handles all FiLLiP filings and the Central Registration Centre (CRC) provides initial scrutiny. The Delhi state stamp duty on both the LLP Agreement (INR 1,000 fixed plus contribution-linked) and the Business Transfer Agreement (conveyance duty if immovable property is included) follows the Indian Stamp Act 1899 Delhi Schedule.</p>

                </div>
                <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-top:20px;">
                    <p><strong>Key Terms for Proprietorship to LLP Conversion:</strong></p>
                    <p><strong>LLP:</strong> Limited Liability Partnership - hybrid body corporate under the LLP Act 2008; separate legal personality; partners have limited liability; minimum 2 designated partners (1 Indian resident); no minimum capital.</p>
<p><strong>FiLLiP:</strong> Form for Incorporation of LLP - integrated MCA21 v3 e-form for name reservation plus incorporation (RUN-LLP merged into FiLLiP in 2018).</p>
<p><strong>Form 3 (LLP):</strong> LLP Agreement filing form; mandatory within 30 days of incorporation; non-filing attracts daily additional fees of INR 100 under Rule 21 LLP Rules 2009.</p>
<p><strong>DPIN:</strong> Designated Partner Identification Number - obtained through FiLLiP for new partners or via Form DIR-3 for existing DIN holders.</p>
<p><strong>Business Transfer Agreement (BTA):</strong> Contract transferring an undertaking from proprietorship to LLP for lump-sum consideration; structured as slump sale where eligible.</p>
<p><strong>Slump Sale (Section 50B):</strong> Tax-specific characterisation under Income Tax Act 1961 - transfer of undertaking as going concern for lump-sum consideration without individual asset valuation; capital gains computed on (sale consideration minus net worth).</p>
<p><strong>Form 3CEA:</strong> CA-certified report mandatory for slump sale under Section 50B(3) read with Rule 11UAE.</p>
<p><strong>Going Concern (GST):</strong> Transfer of business as a whole; nil GST under Notification 12/2017-Central Tax (Rate).</p>
<p><strong>Form GST ITC-02:</strong> Transfers unutilised proprietorship ITC to LLP GSTIN under Rule 41 CGST Rules 2017.</p>
<p><strong>Section 47(xiv) IT Act:</strong> Tax-neutrality for proprietorship-to-COMPANY conversion only; does NOT apply to proprietorship-to-LLP, hence the slump sale route is necessary.</p>
<p><strong>Section 7 LLP Act 2008:</strong> Designated partner requirements - minimum 2; at least 1 Indian resident.</p>

                </div>
            </div>
