<!-- SECTION 4: WHO CAN FILE -->
<section class="content-section" id="who-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Which Proprietors Should Move to LLP (and Which Should Not)</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                
                <p>Moving from proprietorship to LLP is HIGH-VALUE for the following Delhi-NCR profiles:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Proprietors at INR 40 lakh to INR 5 crore turnover:</strong> Where personal liability exposure has outgrown insurance and personal assets.</li>
                    <li><strong>Proprietors planning to onboard a working partner, family member or investor:</strong> LLP can have unlimited partners; minimum 2 to operate.</li>
                    <li><strong>B2B-heavy proprietors:</strong> Whose buyers (PSUs, large corporates, government tenders) prefer dealing with limited-liability entities for procurement.</li>
                    <li><strong>Proprietors approaching banks or NBFCs for working capital:</strong> Lenders typically extend better terms to LLPs than proprietorships of comparable size.</li>
                    <li><strong>Professional service firms:</strong> Architects, designers, consultants, marketing agencies - where partner-based structure with limited liability is naturally suited.</li>
                    <li><strong>Proprietors at the top slab marginal rate:</strong> Effective 35.88% at the highest slab; 30% LLP rate without surcharge at lower turnover is more efficient.</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top:16px;"><strong>NOT optimal for:</strong> Proprietors with turnover below INR 25 lakh and no realistic 2-year growth above this (LLP Form 8 + Form 11 compliance adds overhead without proportional benefit); proprietors planning institutional fundraising, ESOP rollout or IPO (route to Private Limited directly via Section 47(xiv) tax-neutrality); proprietors who cannot identify a second trusted partner (LLP cannot operate with one partner for more than 6 months under Section 6 LLP Act without partner liability becoming unlimited); proprietors with significant capital gains exposure on heavily appreciated business assets (slump sale will trigger tax that may not be recoverable); proprietors needing to preserve specific industry registrations that do not transfer cleanly.</p>

            </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- SECTION 5: OUR SERVICES -->
<section class="content-section" id="services-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Patron Accounting Proprietorship-to-LLP Services - Delhi</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                <div class="table-responsive-wrapper">
                <table>
                    <thead><tr><th>Service</th><th>What We Do</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td>Pre-Move Eligibility and Section 50B Tax Memo</td><td>One-week review covering minimum 2-partner readiness, proprietorship financial cleanliness (last 2-3 years), proposed LLP capital structure, Section 50B slump sale tax exposure projection (capital gains at undertaking level - sale consideration minus net worth per Rule 11UAE) and Delhi state stamp duty on BTA and LLP Agreement.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>LLP Incorporation via FiLLiP</td><td>DSC for both designated partners; DPIN application embedded in FiLLiP; name reservation through integrated RUN-LLP module; LLP Agreement drafting (profit-sharing, capital contribution, management roles, dispute resolution); FiLLiP filing on MCA21 v3; Certificate of Incorporation typically 5-10 working days from FiLLiP submission.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>LLP Agreement and Form 3 Filing</td><td>Stamp duty paid on the LLP Agreement per Delhi state Schedule under Indian Stamp Act 1899 (INR 1,000 fixed plus contribution-linked); Form 3 filed within 30 days of incorporation to avoid daily additional fees of INR 100 under Rule 21 LLP Rules 2009.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Business Transfer Agreement (Slump Sale Structured)</td><td>Drafting the BTA with slump sale recital under Section 50B; net worth computation per Rule 11UAE; CA certification on Form 3CEA mandatory under Section 50B(3); stamp duty paid on the BTA per Delhi state rates (conveyance duty on immovable property components if any).</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>GST Migration with ITC Transfer</td><td>Cancellation of proprietorship GSTIN via Form GST REG-16; new LLP GSTIN via Form GST REG-01; ITC transfer via Form GST ITC-02 with going concern declaration; bridge transactions managed to avoid double GST exposure.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Post-Incorporation Compliance Kit</td><td>Bank account opening for the LLP; Udyam / MSME re-registration; Shop and Establishment re-registration; sector-specific licence re-applications (FSSAI, IEC, Profession Tax) where applicable; PAN and TAN follow-up; first-year compliance calendar with Form 8 (30 October due date next FY) and Form 11 (30 May due date next FY) deadlines.</td></tr>

                    </tbody>
                </table>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- SECTION 7: 7-STEP PROCESS -->
