<!-- SECTION 8: DOCUMENTS REQUIRED -->
<section class="content-section" id="documents-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Documents Checklist for Proprietorship-to-LLP Move</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                
                <ul>
                    <li>PAN and Aadhaar of the sole proprietor and the proposed second (and any additional) partner</li>
                    <li>Passport-size photographs of both designated partners</li>
                    <li>Residential address proof of both partners (electricity bill / bank statement under 2 months)</li>
                    <li>Email IDs and Indian mobile numbers of both partners (for OTP-based MCA verification)</li>
                    <li>Proprietorship business existence proof - GST certificate, Shop and Establishment licence or Udyam / MSME registration</li>
                    <li>Last 2-3 years financial statements of the proprietorship (Balance Sheet and Profit and Loss)</li>
                    <li>Last 2-3 years Income Tax Returns of the proprietor (ITR-3 or ITR-4 depending on business type)</li>
                    <li>List of all assets, liabilities and contracts of the proprietorship as on the proposed BTA effective date</li>
                    <li>Existing GST registration certificate, IEC, FSSAI and other regulatory licences of the proprietorship</li>
                    <li>Delhi registered office proof for the new LLP - rent agreement, NOC from owner, latest utility bill</li>
                    <li>Three proposed LLP names (in case the first is taken or requires referral)</li>
                    <li>Bank statement of the proprietorship for the last 6 months (for valuation and continuity demonstration)</li>
                </ul>

            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- SECTION 9: CHALLENGES -->
<section class="content-section" id="challenges-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Common Challenges and Patron Solutions</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                <div class="table-responsive-wrapper">
                <table>
                    <thead><tr><th>Challenge</th><th>Impact</th><th>How Patron Accounting Solves It</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td>No statutory tax neutrality for proprietorship-to-LLP</td><td>Unlike Section 47(xiv) for proprietorship-to-company conversion, there is no equivalent exemption when the transferee is an LLP. The slump sale under Section 50B is the closest available structure.</td><td>Patron structures the Business Transfer Agreement as a slump sale under Section 50B - capital gains may still apply but are computed at the undertaking level (sale consideration minus net worth) rather than asset-by-asset; long-term capital gains rate applies if the business has been held for more than 36 months. Where the net worth approximates sale consideration (clean BTA at book value), the resulting tax is often minimal.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Identifying a second partner</td><td>LLP cannot operate with one partner for more than 6 months under Section 6 of the LLP Act 2008 without partner liability becoming unlimited.</td><td>Patron works through partner options upfront - spouse, adult family member, long-time employee, working partner or family-trust entity. The LLP Agreement is drafted to clearly define capital contribution, profit-sharing and management roles, so a nominee partner is not exposed to operational risk.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>GST migration timing</td><td>If the proprietorship GSTIN is cancelled before the LLP GSTIN is operational, business operations break down; if both are active too long, double GST exposure arises.</td><td>Patron sequences the migration tightly - LLP GSTIN obtained first, Form GST ITC-02 filed transferring unutilised credit, then proprietorship GSTIN cancelled with the cancellation effective date set to align with the BTA effective date. Bridge transactions are categorised to the correct GSTIN.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Sectoral licence transfers</td><td>Udyam, Shop and Establishment, FSSAI, IEC, drug licence and others typically require fresh application in the LLP name; some take 30-90 days; the proprietorship licences cannot legally be used by the LLP.</td><td>Patron maps sector-specific licences at engagement start; submits re-issuance applications immediately after LLP incorporation; manages the bridge period where the proprietorship continues to hold the licence and operate temporarily while the LLP licence is processed.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Bank account, payment processor and contract migration</td><td>Existing proprietorship contracts, AMCs and customer master records do not transfer automatically.</td><td>The BTA includes assignment clauses for assignable contracts. Counterparty consents are obtained where required (typically institutional customers; retail usually does not need consent). Payment processors require fresh KYC for the LLP. Patron hands over a contract migration checklist and follows up over 30-60 days post-incorporation.</td></tr>
