                <div class="faq-expanded__list">
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-1">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Can a proprietorship be directly converted to an LLP in India?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>No. There is no direct statutory conversion route from sole proprietorship to LLP under Indian law. The Limited Liability Partnership Act 2008 provides explicit conversion procedures only for partnership firms (Section 55), private companies (Section 56) and unlisted public companies (Section 57). The practical mechanism for a proprietor is to incorporate a fresh LLP via FiLLiP and then transfer the business via a Business Transfer Agreement, ideally structured as a slump sale under Section 50B of the Income Tax Act 1961.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-2">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">How do you convert a sole proprietorship to an LLP?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Two main steps. Step One - incorporate a fresh LLP under the LLP Act 2008 by filing FiLLiP on MCA21 v3 with at least two designated partners; the Certificate of Incorporation comes in 5 to 10 working days. Step Two - transfer the proprietorship business to the new LLP via a Business Transfer Agreement (slump sale under Section 50B); cancel the proprietorship GSTIN; obtain new LLP GSTIN; transfer Input Tax Credit via Form GST ITC-02.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-3">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is the cost of converting a proprietorship to LLP in 2026?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Patron Accounting charges INR 14,999 (Exl GST and Govt. Charges) for end-to-end execution in Delhi - covering DSC for two partners, FiLLiP incorporation, LLP Agreement and Form 3, Business Transfer Agreement with Form 3CEA, GST migration with Form GST ITC-02 and primary licence transitions (Udyam and Shop Act). Statutory charges (MCA fees per contribution slab, Delhi stamp duty on LLP Agreement and BTA, DSC vendor charges) are pass-through at actuals.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-4">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">How long does it take to convert proprietorship to LLP?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>End-to-end timeline is 15 to 30 days for standard cases. DSC and DPIN 3-5 working days; FiLLiP name reservation 1-3 days; Certificate of Incorporation 5-10 working days; LLP Agreement and Form 3 filing within 30 days of incorporation; Business Transfer Agreement and GST migration 7-10 working days; sectoral licence re-registrations vary - Udyam and Shop Act 3-7 days, FSSAI 30-60 days, IEC 5-10 days.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-5">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What are the tax implications of converting proprietorship to LLP?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Unlike proprietorship-to-company (which enjoys Section 47(xiv) tax-neutrality under conditions), there is no equivalent exemption for proprietorship-to-LLP. The transfer is taxable under Section 45 of the Income Tax Act 1961. Structured as a slump sale under Section 50B, capital gains are computed at the undertaking level (sale consideration minus net worth per Rule 11UAE) and CA-certified on Form 3CEA. Long-term capital gains rate applies if the business has been held for more than 36 months.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-6">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Does GST need to be re-registered when proprietorship converts to LLP?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Yes. The LLP is a new legal entity and obtains a fresh GSTIN through Form GST REG-01. The proprietorship GSTIN is cancelled via Form GST REG-16. Unutilised Input Tax Credit transfers via Form GST ITC-02 under Rule 41 of the CGST Rules 2017. The transfer of business as a going concern attracts nil GST under Notification 12/2017-Central Tax (Rate). Patron sequences both filings tightly to avoid double-GST exposure during the bridge period.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-7">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Why is there no Section 47(xiv) equivalent for LLP?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Section 47(xiv) of the Income Tax Act 1961 was drafted specifically for proprietorship-to-COMPANY conversion (with the 50% voting power 5-year lock-in being viable only in share-based structures). LLPs use capital contribution not equity shares, so the structural fit does not apply. Section 47(xiiib) exists for company-to-LLP conversion but again does not cover proprietorship-to-LLP. The slump sale route under Section 50B is the closest available tax treatment.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-8">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What if I want to upgrade further from LLP to Private Limited later?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Section 56 of the LLP Act 2008 allows conversion from LLP to private company through a specific procedure (CA-certified compliance with Section 56 + Third Schedule). This is a separate engagement; the original Section 50B slump sale tax position from the proprietorship-to-LLP move continues to apply to the LLP entity. Founders planning institutional fundraising within 18 months should consider the direct proprietorship-to-Pvt-Ltd route under Section 47(xiv) instead - that route is tax-neutral but heavier on compliance.</p></div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Quick Answers -->
            <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-top:32px;">
                <p><strong>Quick Answers</strong></p>
                <p><strong>Q: Mechanism?</strong> A: Fresh LLP incorporation via FiLLiP + Business Transfer Agreement (no direct statutory conversion route under LLP Act 2008).</p>
                <p><strong>Q: LLP governing law?</strong> A: LLP Act 2008 + LLP Rules 2009.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Minimum partners?</strong> A: 2 designated partners; 1 Indian resident under Section 7.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Minimum capital?</strong> A: No minimum capital requirement for LLP.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Core MCA form?</strong> A: FiLLiP (integrated incorporation on MCA21 v3); Form 3 for LLP Agreement within 30 days.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Tax characterisation?</strong> A: Slump sale under Section 50B Income Tax Act 1961; Form 3CEA CA-certified.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: No tax-neutrality?</strong> A: Section 47(xiv) applies to proprietorship-to-COMPANY only, NOT to proprietorship-to-LLP.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: GST?</strong> A: New LLP GSTIN via REG-01; Form GST ITC-02 for ITC transfer on going concern (nil GST under Notification 12/2017-CT(R)); REG-16 for proprietorship cancellation.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Stamp duty?</strong> A: Per Delhi state Schedule under Indian Stamp Act 1899 - on LLP Agreement (INR 1,000 fixed + contribution-linked) and on the BTA.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Timeline?</strong> A: 15 to 30 days end to end.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Form 3 deadline?</strong> A: Within 30 days of LLP incorporation; INR 100 daily additional fees if missed (no cap) under Rule 21 LLP Rules 2009.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Form 11 / Form 8 deadlines?</strong> A: Form 11 by 30 May; Form 8 by 30 October following FY end.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: LLP audit?</strong> A: Above INR 40 lakh turnover OR INR 25 lakh contribution.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Patron fee?</strong> A: INR 14,999 FIXED for end-to-end move including FiLLiP, BTA, Form 3CEA, GST migration and compliance kit.</p>

            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

